          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830633?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿达克岛，阿拉斯加</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：妮可·埃瓦特/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>认为下一场重大战争不会触及美国领土的美国人可能需要注意中国和俄罗斯上周在阿拉斯加海岸附近进行联合海军行动的消息。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>美国官员称，有11艘船只参加了阿留申群岛附近的巡逻活动。这是分析人士记忆中规模最大的一次行动，此前，2022 年 9 月还进行了一次规模较小的行动。这次联合巡逻突显了两国之间的合作，这种合作正在延伸到北京在乌克兰对莫斯科的帮助之外的军事行动。 （见附近的塞思·克罗普西。）</p><p>美国随即出动，派出四艘驱逐舰和侦察机对外国军舰进行跟踪。这比九月事件有所改善，当时阿拉斯加州参议员丹·沙利文批评美国反应不温不火。</p><p>美国北方司令部发言人表示，中俄巡逻队并未被视为威胁，但很快有一天可能会被视为威胁。在大国竞争的新时代，俄罗斯、中国和伊朗正在构建挑战美国实力的轴心。这次海军巡逻最好理解为对美国领土不安全的警告，也是对美国将如何应对的考验。</p><p>世界正变得越来越危险，而自满的美国政治阶层并没有让公众了解日益增长的威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EF98C809-AE43-4880-9FBD-64459B5B35BD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-and-russia-eye-alaska-aleutian-naval-ships-sullivan-a652c8b0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：如何使国会无效。图片：彭博新闻/美联社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 21:35:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-and- Russia-eye-alaska-aleutian-naval-ships-sullivan-a652c8b0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-and- Russia-eye-alaska-aleutian-naval-ships-sullivan-a652c8b0<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>阿留申群岛</category><category>海军舰艇</category><category>阿拉斯加州</category><category>大国竞争</category><category>伊朗</category><category>中国</category><category>俄罗斯</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>阿留申群岛</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Challenge to Racial Politics in Medicine]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>医生提起诉讼，要求停止加州关于教授“隐性偏见”的要求。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122270114872654"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122270114872654"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 6 日下午 5:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawsuit-california-continuing-medical-education-doctors-azadeh-khatibi-marilyn-singleton-15668016"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830636?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>多元化、公平和包容的官僚机构已将进步政治注入私营经济的许多角落，但其在医学领域的作用尤其有害。现在，一场诉讼正在质疑加州是否可以强迫教授继续医学教育课程的医生也教授种族政治。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>根据加州 2019 年的一项强制规定，2022 年之后该州的所有继续医学教育课程都必须包含对“隐性偏见”的讨论。这种观点认为，医生应该怀有种族主义观点，但他们自己没有意识到，因此必须教会他们认识和承认这些观点。所有此类课程都必须包括有关“隐性偏见如何影响内科医生和外科医生的看法和治疗决策，导致健康结果差异”或“解决”意外偏见的策略的课程。</p><p>伊朗出生的眼科医生阿扎德·卡蒂比 (Azadeh Khatibi) 和麻醉师玛丽莲·辛格尔顿 (Marilyn Singleton) 正在挑战加州的这项规定。医生们表示，隐性偏见培训与医生在继续教育课程中涵盖的医学主题无关，并且护理方面的差异不能归因于隐性偏见。</p><p>由医疗组织“不伤害”和太平洋法律基金会提起的诉讼（<em>卡蒂比诉劳森</em>）称，隐性偏见指令相当于强迫言论，侵犯了教师的第一修正案权利。诉讼称，加州“不能以演讲者在有争议的话题上支持政府偏爱的观点为条件来限制演讲者提供学分课程的能力”。</p><p>加州医生必须每两年完成 50 小时的继续医学教育才能更新执照。现在，所有课程都必须包括种族偏见培训才能获得学分，并且必须传达政府首选的信息。</p><p>这些都不需要用来对抗实际的种族歧视，根据加州的《安鲁法案》和各种联邦法律，种族歧视是非法的。如果有种族歧视的证据，医生和医院也可能被起诉。</p><p>加州的医学教育任务是迫使教师强制执行这样的政治信息：医生无论怎么想或做什么都是种族主义者。这对社会礼让是有害的，我们很高兴看到医生指出它对言论自由的影响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=242A26BC-6D31-40E8-BED4-821C14D06E45&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flawsuit-california-continuing-medical-education-doctors-azadeh-khatibi-marilyn-singleton-15668016&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：这都是关于拜登的“品牌”。图片：路透社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 21:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawsuit-california-continuing-medical-education-doctors-azadeh-khatibi-marilyn-singleton-15668016</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/lawsuit-california-continuing-medical-education-doctors-azadeh-khatibi-marilyn-singleton-15668016<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>阿扎德·哈提比</category><category>玛丽莲·辛格尔顿</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>健康</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[August’s Surprises Arrived Early]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>不明飞行物、脑部扫描和超导体使七月变得异常有趣。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128161864182540"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128161864182540"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andy-kessler"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS035_Kessle_AM_20180912114138.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/andy-kessler" itemprop="url" rel="author">安迪·凯斯勒</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 6 日下午 5:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/augusts-surprises-arrived-early-ufos-lk-99-brain2music-news-stock-market-trump-hunter-biden-c153db49"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829398?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 26 日，大卫·格鲁什 (David Grusch) 在华盛顿举行的国会听证会上发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Annabelle Gordon - Cnp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>就好像他们读懂了我的心思。 2021 年，我<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/berlin-wall-arab-spring-color-tv-internet-innovation-investing-11627829703?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">注意到</a>8 月常常会出现惊喜。两周后，拜登总统的阿富汗退出变成了一场意想不到的惨败。我想，嘿，让我们再试一次。在过去的几周里，我研究了一篇关于更多八月惊喜的专栏。想象一下，当七月（甚至是最后一周左右）出现一系列看似相关的惊喜时，我会感到多么惊讶。我撕掉了八月专栏。</p><p>让我们从不明异常现象开始，这是不明飞行物的流行新表达方式。美国前情报特工戴维·格鲁什 (David Grusch) 7 月 26 日向国会作证称，美国不仅取回了不明飞行物，还取回了所谓飞行员的“非人类”生物制品。有图片吗？如果是这样，你想打赌它们是模糊的、有颗粒感的吗？</p><p>我属于认为政府每次需要分散注意力时都会推出不明飞行物的阵营。 2003年，中央情报局解密的文件显示，在飞碟因参与1954年危地马拉政变而被揭发后不久，该局就编造了有关飞碟的故事。不明飞行物的故事是否被用来分散我们对唐纳德·特朗普的起诉或亨特·拜登逃税的注意力？</p><p>也许不明飞行物是真实的。如果是这样，外星人一定拥有一些非常酷的技术，比如支持量子驱动引擎的超导体。你瞧，7月22日，韩国宣布推出常温常压超导体LK-99，让所有人大吃一惊。一段视频声称展示了迈斯纳效应，即当材料变得超导时，通过发射的磁波实现悬浮。</p><p>创作者甚至描述了如何制造铅基超导体。第一步需要由铜粉和红磷合成磷化铜。哎呀，缉毒局将红磷标记为非法冰毒实验室用来将伪麻黄碱转化为甲基苯丙胺的 I 类化学物质。它也出现在随处出击的比赛中。我怀疑每一位试图复制室温超导体的科学家现在都在疯狂观看《绝命毒师》以寻求秘诀。</p><p>复制结果需要时间——几周，或者像许多怀疑论者认为的那样永远。尽管如此，室温超导体仍将迎来磁悬浮列车、手持式磁共振成像、廉价量子计算甚至核聚变的时代。</p><p>在一些令人惊讶的室温思考中，7 月 24 日，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk)</a>将 Twitter 的名称莫名其妙地更改为 X，从而点击了“删除”17 年宝贵的品牌建设。为什么？好吧，随着不明飞行物的热潮，一些前推特用户——看到我在那里做了什么吗？——认为这是对电视节目“X档案”的致敬。比什么都有意义。</p><p>另一方面，这完全没有意义：在一个注意力持续时间越来越短的世界里，数百万人自愿进入暗室，观看连续闪烁的有关玩偶和核物理学家的赛璐珞——巴本海默计时器运行了近五个小时。诡异的。与此同时，最令人惊讶的是，股市在 7 月份进入了平流层。或者是奥本海默式的蘑菇云？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多内部视图</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ais-growing-legal-troubles-section-230-publisher-class-action-9efaf374?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">人工智能日益严重的法律问题</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 30 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/esg-is-blowin-in-the-wind-protest-songs-60s-70s-companies-capitalism-187f5ce4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">ESG 随风而动</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 23 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-innovation-cage-match-facebook-twitter-competition-musk-ai-794e0ebf?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">创新笼比赛</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 16 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>更疯狂的是：7月20日，谷歌和大阪大学的研究人员公布了Brain2Music的详细信息。顾名思义，它根据大脑活动重建音乐——是的，读心术。当一个人听音乐时，功能磁共振成像（功能性磁共振成像）会捕获脑电波。这些数据通过人工智能运行，将声音分解为更小的文本元素，然后将其输入到名为 MusicLM 的文本到音乐转换器中，播放重建的音乐。惊人的。</p><p>他们使用来自 10 个不同流派的 540 个音乐样本测试了结果，其中包括 1986 年 Beastie Boys 的热门歌曲“(You Gotta) Fight for Your Right (to Party)”。重建的输出有点粗糙，但这是真正读心的第一步。所需要的只是便携式核磁共振成像——等等，室温超导体将实现这一点。</p><p>巧合的是，也许不是，7 月 20 日，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果</a>公司提交的一项“使用动态选择电极的生物信号传感设备”专利申请被公布。它看起来像 AirPods，只不过耳机有 40 或 50 个嵌入式电极传感器，可用于“准确测量大脑活动”。嗯。当我们讨论不明飞行物时，这能读懂我们的心思吗？我不会感到惊讶。</p><p>所有这些惊喜都发生在我阅读乔治·吉尔德的著作时</p>很棒的新书，《资本主义之后的生活》。它为经济学信息论提供了一个深思熟虑的案例，其基础是财富就是知识，增长就是学习，信息就是惊喜，金钱就是时间。吉尔德先生解释说，所有科学和经济惊喜都是信息，并且会持续发生，否则我们将生活在一个静态的世界中。<p></p><p>从七月的情况来看，我们当然不属于其中之一。七月提醒我们不要思想封闭。我唯一真正感到惊讶的是这些惊喜并不是在八月。</p><p><em>写信给 kessler@wsj.com。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=574CB8D9-9EF4-4168-9311-463F148B33EB&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Faugusts-surprises-arrived-early-ufos-lk-99-brain2music-news-stock-market-trump-hunter-biden-c153db49&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Conspiracy theories abound, but according to congressional testimony from UFO eyewitnesses, government over-classification is concealing the extent of Unidentified Anomalous Phenomena, or UAP, activity. Images: Getty Images/Dept. of Defense Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 21:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/augusts-surprises-arrived-early-ufos-lk-99-brain2music-news-stock-market-trump-hunter-biden-c153db49</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/augusts-surprises-arrived-early-ufos-lk-99-brain2music-news-stock-market-trump-hunter-biden-c153db49<author><![CDATA[Andy Kessler]]></author><category>飞碟</category><category>cia</category><category> flying saucers</category><category> lk-99</category><category>苹果</category><category>superconducting</category><category>消息</category><category>stock market</category><category> brain2music</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Groundhog Day for Deadbeat Argentina]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Another peso collapse may be coming as a presidential election approaches. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130012376882230"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130012376882230"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/mary-anastasia-ogrady"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI562_ogrady_AM_20180807122707.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/mary-anastasia-ogrady" itemprop="url" rel="author">Mary Anastasia O&#39;Grady</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 6, 2023 5:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/groundhog-day-for-deadbeat-argentina-peso-imf-inflation-collapse-china-yuan-b97551c2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830523?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Patricio Murphy/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Margaret Thatcher famously quipped that the trouble with socialism is that “you eventually run out of other people&#39;s money.” That hasn&#39;t yet happened to the world&#39;s most notorious deadbeat.</p><p> Last week Argentina struck a <a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/china-holds-key-avoiding-argentinas-imf-default-price-tag-is-unknown-2023-08-02/" target="_blank" class="icon none">deal</a> with Beijing to tap nearly $3 billion in yuan from a currency swap line the two countries <a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/currencies/argentina-renew-expand-china-currency-swap-line-2023-06-02/" target="_blank" class="icon none">renewed</a> in June. The announcement, in which China is playing the lender of last resort for Argentina, came two days after the International Monetary Fund reached a preliminary <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2023/07/28/pr23281-imf-and-argentina-reach-staff-level-agreement-on-the-fifth-and-sixth-reviews" target="_blank" class="icon none">agreement</a> with Buenos Aires to unlock access to $7.5 billion. The IMF said the money is “intended to support Argentina&#39;s policy efforts and near-term balance of payments needs, including obligations to the Fund.” In other words, the fund is giving money to its “client” so that the client doesn&#39;t go into arrears on its $44 billion debt to the fund.</p><p> The arrangement needs IMF executive board approval, which may come later this month. Meantime, Argentina has <a href="https://www.infobae.com/economia/2023/08/05/tras-el-pago-al-fmi-con-la-ayuda-de-qatar-y-sin-yuanes-cuanto-queda-del-swap-con-china-para-pagar-importaciones/" target="_blank" class="icon none">used</a> the China loan—and help from Qatar—to stay current with the IMF. (Payment in yuan was an Obama-era enhancement.)</p><p> None of this will solve the fiscal and monetary problems plaguing the country. With inflation running at an annual rate of <a href="https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/economy/argentina-monthly-inflation-slowed-in-june-for-second-straight-month.phtml" target="_blank" class="icon none">115%</a> , there&#39;s no appetite to hold pesos. Net international reserves have plummeted and are now <a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/argentina-economy-reserves/argentina-net-fx-reserves-seen-5-billion-in-the-red-analysts-say-idUSL1N38S349" target="_blank" class="icon none">negative</a> .</p><p> Argentina&#39;s central bank is printing more pesos than the market wants to hold because the government, which is broke, needs them to pay its bills. This isn&#39;t new in Argentina. Successive governments have generated repeated bouts of high inflation for decades. In an August 2019 piece in Forbes, Johns Hopkins economist Steve Hanke <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevehanke/2019/08/12/macris-kiss-of-death-argentinas-peso-and-the-imf/?sh=ffadbb619322" target="_blank" class="icon none">summarized</a> the history: “To list but a few of Argentina&#39;s major peso collapses: 1876, 1890, 1914, 1930, 1952, 1958, 1967, 1975, 1985, 1989, 2001, and 2018.”</p><p> Since Argentine inflation began to take off again in 2007 until the end of 2022, total money supply grew on average 30.7% a year, <a href="https://www.economia.gob.ar/datos/" target="_blank" class="icon none">according</a> to the Ministry of the Economy. Headline inflation grew on average annually at 35.1% according to Nicolás Cachanosky, director of the Center for Free Enterprise at the University of Texas, El Paso.</p><p> Capital controls exacerbate shortages of hard currency. Dollars coming into the country have to flow through the central bank, which exchanges them for pesos. The purchase of dollars for travel abroad or to pay for imports also is done through the central bank. It has more than 10 official exchange rates, none of which reflect the market. The rate at the central bank for retail is around 290 to the dollar while in the black market the rate is about 565.</p><p> Off-loading pesos to hoard dollars is a national pastime for Argentines, who are among the world&#39;s most sophisticated currency speculators. Investors, knowing that they can&#39;t put capital into the country at market rates or get it out when they want, tend to go elsewhere. Stagnating Argentine economic growth is no mystery.</p><p> The central bank has tried to counter its reckless peso-printing by selling high-yielding term instruments to banks. Thirty-day Leliqs, as these vehicles are called, now carry an effective annualized rate of some <a href="https://bcra.gob.ar/Pdfs/PublicacionesEstadisticas/Bol0623.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">155%</a> . The aim is to sop up excess pesos in circulation.</p><p> Yet even with a healthy Leliq spread over current inflation, demand for the currency is falling. Perhaps it&#39;s because Argentines expect future inflation to be even higher and they understand the risks of a further selloff that would likely trigger a hyperinflationary spiral. This is particularly true in a presidential election year. An unexpected political shock, such as the country experienced in August 2019, could mean that when the central bank tries to roll over the <a href="https://www.cato.org/briefing-paper/argentina-should-dollarize-pronto#liquidity-note-time-bomb" target="_blank" class="icon none">$30 billion</a> in Leliqs outstanding it won&#39;t find buyers. In that case a flood of pesos would hit the economy.</p><p> Argentine authorities are blaming the monetary crisis on weather, and the IMF agrees somewhat. In its rationale for the latest agreement to release new funds, despite the failure of Buenos Aires to meet “key program targets,” the fund pointed to the extended drought affecting agricultural output. Yet it quickly added that fault also lies with “policy slippage and delays,” which seems to be the better explanation for the mess. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Americas</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amlo-plays-a-shell-game-with-pemex-mexico-explosion-debt-corruption-rescue-oil-production-9eb55e0a?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">AMLO Plays a Shell Game With Pemex</a> <span class="date">July 30, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amlo-makes-xochitl-a-household-name-mexico-presidential-election-coalition-64299752?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Mexico&#39;s AMLO Makes Xóchitl a Household Name</a> <span class="date">July 16, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/colonial-joe-biden-bullies-a-neighbor-populism-election-guatemala-populism-race-south-america-d4ab1cdb?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Colonial Joe Biden Bullies a Neighbor</a> <span class="date">July 9, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Neighboring Brazil also has <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/brazil-drought-threatening-national-output-potential-southern-farmers-say-2023-02-14/" target="_blank" class="icon none">experienced</a> a drought. Yet <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/brazil-inflation-down-by-more-than-expected-month-mid-july-2023-07-25/" target="_blank" class="icon none">Brazilian inflation</a> is running at 3.19%, comparable to the US Kudos go to Brazilian central bank president Roberto Campos Neto—and his board—who tightened credit when government spending threatened to undermine price stability. The central bank has held its overnight lending rate at 13.75% for the past year despite <a href="https://www.marketwatch.com/story/brazil-s-president-lula-criticizes-central-bank-s-rates-policy-137df083" target="_blank" class="icon none">pressure</a> from President Luis Inácio “Lula” da Silva to pursue an easier policy.</p><p> On Aug. 13 Argentines vote in primaries for presidential candidates, and this issue is front and center. Yet promises of a cure are short on details, probably because it would mean upending the long tradition of Peronist populism that has bankrupted the country.</p><p> <em>Write to O&#39;Grady@wsj.com.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
